{"title_page": "Larrissa Willcox", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand netball player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n|name    = Larrissa Willcox\n|image   =\n|caption =\n|updated = 2009-10-22\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|11|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height       = {{height|m=1.82|precision=0}}\n|positions     = GK, GD, WD\n|clubyears1 = 2010\n|clubteam1  = [[Northern Mystics]]\n|clubyears2 = 2009\n|clubteam2  = [[Canterbury Tactix]]\n|clubyears3 = 2008 \n|clubteam3  = [[West Coast Fever]]\n|clubyears4 = 2002\u201307\n|clubteam4  = [[Perth Orioles]]\n|nationalyears1 = 2009\n|nationalteam1  = {{nb|New Zealand}}\n|nationalcaps1  = 3\n}}\n'''Larrissa Willcox''' (born 27 November 1982) is a [[New Zealand]] [[netball]] player. She played for the [[West Coast Fever]] in the [[2008 ANZ Championship season]], having played for the same team in Australia's [[Commonwealth Bank Trophy]] from 2002\u201307, when the team was known as the Perth Orioles. In 2009, she switched to New Zealand franchise the [[Canterbury Tactix]], and that same year made her debut for the New Zealand national netball team, the Silver Ferns.\n\nOn 17 September 2009, she announced she was leaving the [[Canterbury Tactix]] and transferring to the [[Northern Mystics]], joining fellow Silver Ferns [[Maria Tutaia]] and [[Joline Henry]], who defected from their [[Waikato Bay of Plenty Magic]] franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10597853|title=Netball: Willcox latest Silver Fern to join trek north|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=17 September 2009|accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mynetball.co.nz/silver-ferns/player-profiles/larrissa-willcox.html Silver Ferns profile: Larrissa Willcox]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706110415/http://netballwa.com.au/extra.asp?id=3042&OrgID=25 2008 West Coast Fever team profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081014135603/http://anz-championship.com/Playerprofile.asp?id=872115&comp=4999&orgid=2344&team=16622 2008 ANZ Championship profile]\n\n{{Silver Ferns squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Willcox, Larrissa}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:West Coast Fever players]]\n[[Category:Mainland Tactix players]]\n[[Category:Northern Mystics players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-netball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n|name    = Larrissa Willcox\n|image   =\n|caption =\n|updated = 2009-10-22\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|11|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height       = {{height|m=1.82|precision=0}}\n|positions     = GK, GD, WD\n|clubyears1 = 2010\n|clubteam1  = [[Northern Mystics]]\n|clubyears2 = 2009\n|clubteam2  = [[Canterbury Tactix]]\n|clubyears3 = 2008 \n|clubteam3  = [[West Coast Fever]]\n|clubyears4 = 2002\u201307\n|clubteam4  = [[Perth Orioles]]\n|nationalyears1 = 2009\n|nationalteam1  = {{nb|New Zealand}}\n|nationalcaps1  = 3\n}}\n'''Larrissa Willcox''' (born 27 November 1982) is a [[New Zealand]] [[netball]] player. She played for the [[West Coast Fever]] in the [[2008 ANZ Championship season]], having played for the same team in Australia's [[Commonwealth Bank Trophy]] from 2002\u201307, when the team was known as the Perth Orioles. In 2009, she switched to New Zealand franchise the [[Canterbury Tactix]], and that same year made her debut for the New Zealand national netball team, the Silver Ferns.\n\nOn 17 September 2009, she announced she was leaving the [[Canterbury Tactix]] and transferring to the [[Northern Mystics]], joining fellow Silver Ferns [[Maria Tutaia]] and [[Joline Henry]], who defected from their [[Waikato Bay of Plenty Magic]] franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10597853|title=Netball: Willcox latest Silver Fern to join trek north|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=17 September 2009|accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mynetball.co.nz/silver-ferns/player-profiles/larrissa-willcox.html Silver Ferns profile: Larrissa Willcox]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706110415/http://netballwa.com.au/extra.asp?id=3042&OrgID=25 2008 West Coast Fever team profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081014135603/http://anz-championship.com/Playerprofile.asp?id=872115&comp=4999&orgid=2344&team=16622 2008 ANZ Championship profile]\n\n{{Silver Ferns squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Willcox, Larrissa}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:West Coast Fever players]]\n[[Category:Mainland Tactix players]]\n[[Category:Northern Mystics players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-netball-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"New Zealand netball player\", overriding Wikidata description \"New Zealand netball player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larrissa_Willcox"}
{"title_page": "Donna Wilkins", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand netball and basketball player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n|name    = Donna Wilkins \n|image= \n|caption =\n|updated = \n|fullname     = Donna Wilkins ([[n\u00e9e]] Loffhagen)\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|04|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Christchurch, New Zealand]] \n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height       = {{height|m=1.85|precision=0}}\n|spouse       = Mike Wilkins\n|children     = 2 sons (Cooper and Jack)<ref name=stuff>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/netball/5698941/Family-help-Donna-Wilkins-to-join-Southern-Steel|title=Family help Donna Wilkins to join Southern Steel|work=The Southland Times|date=28 September 2011|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n|marrieddate  = 17 March 2007\n|positions     = GS, GA\n|clubteam1     = [[Southern Sting]]\n|clubyears1    = 1998-2007, 2009\n|clubteam2     = [[Mainland Tactix]]\n|clubyears2    = 2011\n|clubteam3     = [[Southern Steel]]\n|clubyears3    = 2012\n|clubteam4     = [[Central Pulse]]\n|clubyears4    = 2013-2014\n|nationalteam1  = [[Silver Ferns]]\n|nationalyears1 = 1996-2002\n|nationalcaps1  = 56\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{nb|New Zealand}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Netball World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1999 Netball World Championships|1999 Christchurch]]|[[Netball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalSilver|[[1998 Commonwealth Games|1998 Kuala Lumpur]]|[[Netball at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|Netball]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2002 Commonwealth Games|2002 Manchester]]|[[Netball at the 2002 Commonwealth Games|Netball]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Donna Wilkins''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Loffhagen''') (born 29 April 1978 in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand) is a New Zealand representative in [[netball]] and [[basketball]]. She married Southland farmer Mike Wilkins on 17 March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|author=Burdon, Nathan|title=Donna Loffhagen, Mike Wilkins pronounced husband and wife|work=[[The Southland Times]]|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070317/281586646142582|date=17 March 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Wilkins returned to the [[Southern Steel]] for the 2012 season, after a short stint with the [[Mainland Tactix|Canterbury Tactix]] in 2011.\n\n==Netball==\nWilkins has represented the New Zealand [[New Zealand national netball team|Silver Ferns]] 56 times, making her 50th cap against Barbados in [[Auckland]], New Zealand. The 1.85&nbsp;cm, Goal Attack and Goal Shoot, started her career for [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]] in the National Championships in 1994 as a cool sixteen-year-old. She carried on playing for the province until called into the Silver Ferns in 1996. After four years playing top netball in Canterbury, Donna Wilkins signed with the Southland netball team for the 1997 season along with fellow Silver Ferns captain [[Bernice Mene]]. She shot the southerners into fourth place overall in the championships, a much improved performance of 10th the year before.\n\nAfter Netball New Zealand announced plans for a new semi-professional franchise competition for 1998 season to replace the old provincial champs, the new [[Invercargill]] based franchise the [[Southern Sting]] retained Wilkins services along with Bernice Mene for the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070206/28226954592775|title=Ferguson 'rapt' to make captain|work=The Southland Times|date=6 February 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref>\n\nDuring the season Wilkins had scored 38 out of 51 goals against [[Otago Rebels]] but eventually lost the championship 57 to 51.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/sport/netball/back-day-rebels-crowned-national-league-champions|title=Back in the day: Rebels crowned national league champions|author=Meikle, Hayden|work=[[Otago Daily Times]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe continued to play in the South for the Southern Sting till 2006, when she was called into the Suns basketball team in the American [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] basketball competition.<ref name=nzh>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10009317|title=Netball: Loffhagen pulls out of Silver Ferns for basketball|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=3 February 2005|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> She returned for the Stings semi final and final game during which she led them to win the semi final game 64-41 against the [[Northern Force]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070625/282286725851925|title=Sting's decade of excellence 10 straight final appearances|work=[[The Southland Times]]|date=25 June 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref> along with the final winning over [[Waikato Bay of Plenty Magic]] in the 2007 [[National Bank Cup]] with a score of 48-46.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-press/20070616/282810711858332|title=Sting defeat of Magic leads to 10th final|work=The Press|date=16 June 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref>\n\nThe Sting won seven out of the ten National Bank Cup titles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10432596|title=Netball: National Championship teams|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=4 April 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> being named as one of the world's best sporting teams. Other big names to play for the franchise include: [[Bernice Mene]], [[Tania Dalton]], [[Megan Hutton]], [[Belinda Colling]], [[Leana de Bruin]], [[Liana Leota]], [[Adine Wilson]], [[Lesley Rumball]], Naomi Siddall, [[Wendy Frew]], [[Erika Burgess]], [[Daneka Wipiiti]] and [[Natalie Avellino]].\n\nIn 2008 a new trans-Tasman semi-professional league was launched, the [[ANZ Championship]]. Wilkins did not play in the first season due to pregnancy, but continued with the [[Southern Steel]] as an assistant coach. She returned to the playing lineup for the 2009 season,<ref>{{cite news|author=Burdon, Nathan|title=Loffhagen's return to Sting prompts rule change from Netball New Zealand|work=Southland Times|url=http://www.netballsouthland.org.nz/sting/html/14_nov_2006_-_loffhagen_s_retu.html|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=13 May 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> where the Steel improved on their 2008 standing to reach the finals stage; the Steel were eventually defeated by the [[Adelaide Thunderbirds]] in the semi-finals. Later that month, Wilkins announced that she would not be returning to the Steel in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/new-zealand/news/article.cfm?l_id=71&objectid=10585721|date=21 July 2009|author=Johannsen, Dana|title=Wilkins hangs up Southern Steel bib|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilkins turned out for the [[Mainland Tactix|Canterbury Tactix]] in 2011,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/sport/netball/netball-wilkins-excited-canterbury-challenge|title=Netball: Wilkins excited by Canterbury challenge|author=Seconi, Adrian|work=Otago Daily Times|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> and for the next season returned to Southern Steel which she did with family help.<ref name=stuff/>\n\nAs a member of the [[New Zealand national netball team]], Loffhagen won two [[Commonwealth Games]] silver medals, at Kuala Lumpur in 1998 and Manchester in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/donna-wilkins/|title=Donna Wilkins|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\nWilkins formerly played for Canterbury in the NZ Women's Basketball League. In Australia, she played two seasons with the [[Canberra Capitals]] in the [[Women's National Basketball League|WNBL]].<ref name=nz>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=3606477|title=Basketball: Loffhagen's off|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=3 February 2005|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> Prior to joining with the Canberra Capitals she also was on the [[Christchurch Sirens]] which won 76-55 against [[Dandenong Rangers]] and earned her a [[Most Valuable Player]] award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/6061/Wilkins-gets-MVP-award-after-Sirens-first-win|title=Wilkins gets MVP award after Sirens' first win|website=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|date=31 January 2009|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> In 2006, she signed for the [[Connecticut Sun]]s in the US WNBA.<ref name=nzh/>\n\nAs of 2006, Wilkins had 95 caps for [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|New Zealand national team]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=3990|title=The Multi Talented Donna Loffhagen|publisher=[[New Zealand Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=13 February 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20061010125121/http://www.commonwealthgames.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=3990|archivedate=10 October 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> including the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney, the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens (where she played for [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|Tall Ferns]]),<ref name=nz/> and the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in Melbourne (as captain).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New Zealand Women Basketball Squad 2000 Summer Olympics}}\n{{2000 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{2004 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{2006 New Zealand Commonwealth Games team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilkins, Donna}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Australia]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Southern Steel players]]\n[[Category:Mainland Tactix players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Capitals players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2006 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rangiora High School]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in netball]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in basketball]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n|name    = Donna Wilkins \n|image= \n|caption =\n|updated = \n|fullname     = Donna Wilkins ([[n\u00e9e]] Loffhagen)\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|04|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Christchurch, New Zealand]] \n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height       = {{height|m=1.85|precision=0}}\n|spouse       = Mike Wilkins\n|children     = 2 sons (Cooper and Jack)<ref name=stuff>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/netball/5698941/Family-help-Donna-Wilkins-to-join-Southern-Steel|title=Family help Donna Wilkins to join Southern Steel|work=The Southland Times|date=28 September 2011|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n|marrieddate  = 17 March 2007\n|positions     = GS, GA\n|clubteam1     = [[Southern Sting]]\n|clubyears1    = 1998-2007, 2009\n|clubteam2     = [[Mainland Tactix]]\n|clubyears2    = 2011\n|clubteam3     = [[Southern Steel]]\n|clubyears3    = 2012\n|clubteam4     = [[Central Pulse]]\n|clubyears4    = 2013-2014\n|nationalteam1  = [[Silver Ferns]]\n|nationalyears1 = 1996-2002\n|nationalcaps1  = 56\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{nb|New Zealand}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Netball World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1999 Netball World Championships|1999 Christchurch]]|[[Netball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalSilver|[[1998 Commonwealth Games|1998 Kuala Lumpur]]|[[Netball at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|Netball]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2002 Commonwealth Games|2002 Manchester]]|[[Netball at the 2002 Commonwealth Games|Netball]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Donna Wilkins''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Loffhagen''') (born 29 April 1978 in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand) is a New Zealand representative in [[netball]] and [[basketball]]. She married Southland farmer Mike Wilkins on 17 March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|author=Burdon, Nathan|title=Donna Loffhagen, Mike Wilkins pronounced husband and wife|work=[[The Southland Times]]|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070317/281586646142582|date=17 March 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Wilkins returned to the [[Southern Steel]] for the 2012 season, after a short stint with the [[Mainland Tactix|Canterbury Tactix]] in 2011.\n\n==Netball==\nWilkins has represented the New Zealand [[New Zealand national netball team|Silver Ferns]] 56 times, making her 50th cap against Barbados in [[Auckland]], New Zealand. The 1.85&nbsp;cm, Goal Attack and Goal Shoot, started her career for [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]] in the National Championships in 1994 as a cool sixteen-year-old. She carried on playing for the province until called into the Silver Ferns in 1996. After four years playing top netball in Canterbury, Donna Wilkins signed with the Southland netball team for the 1997 season along with fellow Silver Ferns captain [[Bernice Mene]]. She shot the southerners into fourth place overall in the championships, a much improved performance of 10th the year before.\n\nAfter Netball New Zealand announced plans for a new semi-professional franchise competition for 1998 season to replace the old provincial champs, the new [[Invercargill]] based franchise the [[Southern Sting]] retained Wilkins services along with Bernice Mene for the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070206/28226954592775|title=Ferguson 'rapt' to make captain|work=The Southland Times|date=6 February 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref>\n\nDuring the season Wilkins had scored 38 out of 51 goals against [[Otago Rebels]] but eventually lost the championship 57 to 51.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/sport/netball/back-day-rebels-crowned-national-league-champions|title=Back in the day: Rebels crowned national league champions|author=Meikle, Hayden|work=[[Otago Daily Times]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe continued to play in the South for the Southern Sting till 2006, when she was called into the Suns basketball team in the American [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] basketball competition.<ref name=nzh>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10009317|title=Netball: Loffhagen pulls out of Silver Ferns for basketball|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=3 February 2005|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> She returned for the Stings semi final and final game during which she led them to win the semi final game 64-41 against the [[Northern Force]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-southland-times/20070625/282286725851925|title=Sting's decade of excellence 10 straight final appearances|work=[[The Southland Times]]|date=25 June 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref> along with the final winning over [[Waikato Bay of Plenty Magic]] in the 2007 [[National Bank Cup]] with a score of 48-46.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-press/20070616/282810711858332|title=Sting defeat of Magic leads to 10th final|work=The Press|date=16 June 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=PressReader}}</ref>\n\nThe Sting won seven out of the ten National Bank Cup titles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10432596|title=Netball: National Championship teams|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=4 April 2007|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> being named as one of the world's best sporting teams. Other big names to play for the franchise include: [[Bernice Mene]], [[Tania Dalton]], [[Megan Hutton]], [[Belinda Colling]], [[Leana de Bruin]], [[Liana Leota]], [[Adine Wilson]], [[Lesley Rumball]], Naomi Siddall, [[Wendy Frew]], [[Erika Burgess]], [[Daneka Wipiiti]] and [[Natalie Avellino]].\n\nIn 2008 a new trans-Tasman semi-professional league was launched, the [[ANZ Championship]]. Wilkins did not play in the first season due to pregnancy, but continued with the [[Southern Steel]] as an assistant coach. She returned to the playing lineup for the 2009 season,<ref>{{cite news|author=Burdon, Nathan|title=Loffhagen's return to Sting prompts rule change from Netball New Zealand|work=Southland Times|url=http://www.netballsouthland.org.nz/sting/html/14_nov_2006_-_loffhagen_s_retu.html|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=13 May 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> where the Steel improved on their 2008 standing to reach the finals stage; the Steel were eventually defeated by the [[Adelaide Thunderbirds]] in the semi-finals. Later that month, Wilkins announced that she would not be returning to the Steel in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/new-zealand/news/article.cfm?l_id=71&objectid=10585721|date=21 July 2009|author=Johannsen, Dana|title=Wilkins hangs up Southern Steel bib|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilkins turned out for the [[Mainland Tactix|Canterbury Tactix]] in 2011,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/sport/netball/netball-wilkins-excited-canterbury-challenge|title=Netball: Wilkins excited by Canterbury challenge|author=Seconi, Adrian|work=Otago Daily Times|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> and for the next season returned to Southern Steel which she did with family help.<ref name=stuff/>\n\nAs a member of the [[New Zealand national netball team]], Loffhagen won two [[Commonwealth Games]] silver medals, at Kuala Lumpur in 1998 and Manchester in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/donna-wilkins/|title=Donna Wilkins|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\nWilkins formerly played for Canterbury in the NZ Women's Basketball League. In Australia, she played two seasons with the [[Canberra Capitals]] in the [[Women's National Basketball League|WNBL]].<ref name=nz>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=3606477|title=Basketball: Loffhagen's off|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=3 February 2005|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> Prior to joining with the Canberra Capitals she also was on the [[Christchurch Sirens]] which won 76-55 against [[Dandenong Rangers]] and earned her a [[Most Valuable Player]] award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/6061/Wilkins-gets-MVP-award-after-Sirens-first-win|title=Wilkins gets MVP award after Sirens' first win|website=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|date=31 January 2009|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> In 2006, she signed for the [[Connecticut Sun]]s in the US WNBA.<ref name=nzh/>\n\nAs of 2006, Wilkins had 95 caps for [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|New Zealand national team]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=3990|title=The Multi Talented Donna Loffhagen|publisher=[[New Zealand Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=13 February 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20061010125121/http://www.commonwealthgames.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=3990|archivedate=10 October 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> including the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney, the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens (where she played for [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|Tall Ferns]]),<ref name=nz/> and the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in Melbourne (as captain).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New Zealand Women Basketball Squad 2000 Summer Olympics}}\n{{2000 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{2004 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{2006 New Zealand Commonwealth Games team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilkins, Donna}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Australia]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Southern Steel players]]\n[[Category:Mainland Tactix players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Capitals players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2006 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rangiora High School]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in netball]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in basketball]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"New Zealand netball and basketball player\", overriding Wikidata description \"New Zealand netball and basketball player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donna_Wilkins"}
{"title_page": "Daya Wiffen", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand netball player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n |name    = Daya Wiffen\n |image   = \n |caption =\n |updated = 7 December 2012\n<!-- Personal information -->\n |fullname     =\n |maidenname   =\n |birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|03|07|df=yes}}\n |birth_place = \n |death_date  =\n |death_place =\n |height       = {{height|m=1.74|precision=0}}\n |school       = \n |university   = \n |occupation   =\n |relatives    = \n |spouse       = \n |marrieddate  =\n |children     =\n<!-- Netball career -->\n |positions     = C, WD\n |clubyears1 = 2010-present\n |clubteam1  = [[Central Pulse]]\n |clubapps1  =\n |nationalyears1 = 2011\n |nationalteam1  = NZA Squad\n |nationalcaps1  =  }}\n'''Daya Wiffen''' ([[n\u00e9e]] Pritchard; born 7 March 1983) is a New Zealand [[netball]] player who plays in the [[ANZ Championship]], playing for the [[Central Pulse]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Daya Wiffen looks to impress Pulse coach |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/netball/6813095/Daya-Wiffen-looks-to-impress-Pulse-coach |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012 }}</ref> Daya made her debut for the Pulse in 2010, getting regular court time at both C and WD. In 2011, she was the starting C and in 2012 spent most of the season on the bench, but occasionally came on at C. She has resigned to play for the Pulse for 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamish Bidwell |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/5751474/Mother-to-be-Pritchard-picked-for-national-squad |title=Mother-to-be Pritchard picked for national squad |website=Stuff.co.nz |date=2011-10-07 |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she was named in the NZ Accelerant squad.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nikki Macdonald |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/capital-life/6630621/Netball-mum-back-on-the-court |title=Netball mum back on the court |website=Stuff.co.nz |date=2012-03-26 |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\nDaya Wiffen has three children to her husband Sam Wiffen.{{cn|date=May 2016}}\n\nDaya, although very good at netball, is not very good at messenger basketball. She enjoys Pita Pit salads and also likes Thai takeaway and Burger Wisconsin. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiffen, Daya}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:Central Pulse players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-netball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n |name    = Daya Wiffen\n |image   = \n |caption =\n |updated = 7 December 2012\n<!-- Personal information -->\n |fullname     =\n |maidenname   =\n |birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|03|07|df=yes}}\n |birth_place = \n |death_date  =\n |death_place =\n |height       = {{height|m=1.74|precision=0}}\n |school       = \n |university   = \n |occupation   =\n |relatives    = \n |spouse       = \n |marrieddate  =\n |children     =\n<!-- Netball career -->\n |positions     = C, WD\n |clubyears1 = 2010-present\n |clubteam1  = [[Central Pulse]]\n |clubapps1  =\n |nationalyears1 = 2011\n |nationalteam1  = NZA Squad\n |nationalcaps1  =  }}\n'''Daya Wiffen''' ([[n\u00e9e]] Pritchard; born 7 March 1983) is a New Zealand [[netball]] player who plays in the [[ANZ Championship]], playing for the [[Central Pulse]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Daya Wiffen looks to impress Pulse coach |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/netball/6813095/Daya-Wiffen-looks-to-impress-Pulse-coach |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012 }}</ref> Daya made her debut for the Pulse in 2010, getting regular court time at both C and WD. In 2011, she was the starting C and in 2012 spent most of the season on the bench, but occasionally came on at C. She has resigned to play for the Pulse for 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamish Bidwell |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/5751474/Mother-to-be-Pritchard-picked-for-national-squad |title=Mother-to-be Pritchard picked for national squad |website=Stuff.co.nz |date=2011-10-07 |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she was named in the NZ Accelerant squad.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nikki Macdonald |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/capital-life/6630621/Netball-mum-back-on-the-court |title=Netball mum back on the court |website=Stuff.co.nz |date=2012-03-26 |accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\nDaya Wiffen has three children to her husband Sam Wiffen.{{cn|date=May 2016}}\n\nDaya, although very good at netball, is not very good at messenger basketball. She enjoys Pita Pit salads and also likes Thai takeaway and Burger Wisconsin. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiffen, Daya}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand netball players]]\n[[Category:Central Pulse players]]\n[[Category:ANZ Championship players]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-netball-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"New Zealand netball player\", overriding Wikidata description \"New Zealand netball player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daya_Wiffen"}
{"title_page": "Tiburcio V\u00e1squez", "text_new": "{{short description|Californian bandit}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Tiburcio Vasquez\n| image_name = Tiburcio Vasquez.png\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1835|04|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Monterey]], [[Alta California]], [[First Mexican Republic]]<br/>{{small|(today [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]])}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1875|03|19|1835|08|11}}\n| death_place = [[San Jose, California|San Jos\u00e9]], California \n| death_cause = [[Execution by hanging]]\n| conviction = Murder\n| conviction_penalty = Death by hanging\n| conviction_status = Executed\n}}\n\n'''Tiburcio Vasquez''' (April 11, 1835 \u2013 March 19, 1875) was a [[Californio]] [[Outlaw|''bandido'']] who was active in [[California]] from 1854 to 1874. The [[Vasquez Rocks]], {{convert|40|mi}} north of [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], were one of his many hideouts and are named after him.\n\n== Early life ==\nTiburcio Vasquez was born in [[Monterey]], [[Alta California]], Mexico (present-day [[California]], United States) on April 11, 1835 to Jos\u00e9 Hermenegildo Vasquez and Mar\u00eda Guadalupe Cantua.<ref name=\"Acu\u00f1a\">{{harvnb|Acu\u00f1a|2011|p=140}}</ref><ref name=\"Boessenecker_013\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|p=13}}</ref> In accord with Spanish tradition, Vasquez's birth was celebrated on the feast day of his namesake, St. Tiburtius. Thus, he always referred to his birthday as August 11, 1835.<ref name=\"Boessenecker\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010}}</ref> His great-grandfather came to Alta California with the [[De Anza Expedition]] of 1776. Vasquez was slightly built,  about {{convert|5|ft|7|in|cm}}. His family sent him to school, and he was fluent in both English and Spanish.\n\nIn 1852, Vasquez was influenced by [[Anastacio Garc\u00eda]], one of California's most dangerous bandits.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_046\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=46\u201348}}</ref> In 1854, Vasquez was present at the slaying of Monterey Constable William Hardmount in a fight with Anastacio Garc\u00eda at a [[fandango (dance)|fandango]]. Vasquez denied any involvement and fled, becoming an outlaw. Vasquez later claimed his crimes were the result of discrimination by the ''norteamericanos'' and insisted that he was a defender of Mexican-American rights.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_049\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=49\u201353}}</ref> Vasquez and Garc\u00eda played leading roles in Monterey County's murderous Roach-Belcher feud, which ended when Garc\u00eda was executed by hanging in 1875.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_054-069\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=54\u201369}}</ref>\n\nBy 1856, Vasquez was rustling horses. A sheriff's posse caught up with him near [[Santa Clarita, California|Newhall]], and he spent the next five years behind bars in [[San Quentin]] prison. There he helped organize, and participated in, four bloody prison breaks which left twenty convicts dead.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_070\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=70\u2013101}}</ref> After his release, he committed numerous burglaries, cattle thefts, and highway robberies in Sonoma County in 1866. He was captured after a store burglary in [[Petaluma]] and sent to prison again for three years.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_102\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=102\u2013120}}</ref> His \"trademark\" was \"binding [his victims'] hands behind their back and leaving them face down in the dust.\"<ref name=\"Roddy\">{{harvnb|Roddy|1970}}</ref>\n\n== Final years ==\nIn 1870, Vasquez organized a bandit gang, which included the notorious Juan Soto, and later, [[Procopio|Procopio Bustamante]]. After numerous bandit raids, he was shot and badly wounded in a gunfight with [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]] police officer Robert Liddell. He managed to escape, and his sisters nursed him back to health.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_165\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=165\u2013172}}</ref>\n\nIn 1873, he gained statewide, and then nationwide, notoriety. Vasquez and his gang stole $2,200 from Snyder's Store in [[Tres Pinos]], now called [[Paicines, California|Paicines]], in [[San Benito County]]. Three were killed, but not by Tiburcio. [[Posse Comitatus (Common Law)|Posses]] began searching for him, and Governor [[Newton Booth]] placed a $1,000 reward on his head. Sheriff John H. Adams from San Jose pursued the band to Southern California; Vasquez escaped after a gunfight.<ref>{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=213\u2013241}}</ref>\n\nVasquez hid for a while in Southern California, where he was less well known. With his two most trusted men, he rode over the [[Tejon Pass (Kern County)|old Tejon Pass]], through the [[Antelope Valley]], and rested at Jim Hefner's ranch at [[Elizabeth Lake (Los Angeles County, California)|Elizabeth Lake]]. Vasquez's brother, Francisco, lived nearby. After resting, Vasquez rode on to [[Littlerock, California|Littlerock]] Creek, which became his first [[Southern California]] hideout.\n\nVasquez was popular in the Mexican-American community, and had many friends and family members from Santa Rosa in Northern California to Los Angeles in the south. He was handsome, literate, charming, played guitar, and was a skillful dancer. Women were attracted to him and he had many love affairs. He enjoyed reading romantic novels and writing poetry for his female admirers. He had several affairs with married women, one of which eventually led to his downfall.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_139\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=139\u2013140, 206\u2013207, 233\u2013234}}</ref>\n\nVasquez returned to the San Joaquin Valley. On November 10, 1873, he and his gang robbed the Jones store at Millerton in Fresno County. On December 26, 1873, he and his band sacked the town of [[Kingston, California|Kingston]] in [[Fresno County]], robbing all the businesses and making off with $2,500 in cash and jewelry.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_250\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=250\u2013268}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Booth was now authorized by the California State Legislature to spend up to $15,000 to bring the law down on Vasquez. Posses were formed in [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]], [[Monterey County, California|Monterey]], [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]], Fresno, and [[Tulare County, California|Tulare]] counties. In January 1874, Booth offered $3,000 for Vasquez's capture alive, and $2,000 if he was brought back dead. These rewards were increased in February to $8,000 and $6,000, respectively. [[Alameda County, California|Alameda County]] Sheriff Harry Morse was assigned specifically to track down Vasquez.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_271\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=271\u2013285}}</ref>\n\nHeading towards [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], Vasquez and gang member, Clodoveo Ch\u00e1vez, rode to the rock promontory near [[Inyokern, California|Inyokern]] now known as [[Robbers Roost (Kern County, California)|Robbers Roost]]. Near that spot, at Coyote Holes, they robbed a stagecoach from the [[Cerro Gordo Mines]], silver mines near [[Owens Lake]]. During the robbery Vasquez shot and wounded a man who did not obey his orders.\n\nThe gang moved to Elizabeth Lake and [[Soledad Canyon]], robbing a stage of $300, stealing six horses and a wagon near present-day [[Acton, California|Acton]], and robbing lone travelers. Vasquez was believed to be hiding out at Vasquez Rocks.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_289\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=289\u2013290}}</ref> These rock formations proved a formidable hideout for him and his gang. Shallow caves, deep crevices, and numerous overhangs created a maze for any posse to thread. The tallest rock, 150 feet (46&nbsp;m) high, provided an excellent lookout point.\n\nFor the next two months, he escaped attention. However, he then made an error that led to his capture. On April 15, 1874, he and his band held the prominent sheepman, Alessandro Repetto, for ransom. Pursuing posses from Los Angeles almost trapped the gang in the San Gabriel Mountains, but once again, Vasquez and his men escaped.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_293\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=293\u2013302}}</ref>\n\n== Capture ==\n[[File:Map of Tiburcio V\u00e1squez Capture.jpg|thumb|Vintage Map of Tiburcio V\u00e1squez Capture]]\nVasquez took up residence at the adobe home of [[Yiorgos Caralambo|\"Greek George\" Caralambo]] in the northwest corner of [[Rancho La Brea]], located 200 yards (183&nbsp;m) south of the present-day [[Sunset Strip]] in [[West Hollywood]]. Greek George was a former [[camel]] driver for General [[Edward Fitzgerald Beale|Beale]] in the [[United States Army|Army]] [[U.S. Camel Corps|Camel Corps]]. Allegedly, Vasquez seduced and impregnated his own niece. Either the girl's family or Greek George's wife's family betrayed Vasquez to Los Angeles Sheriff [[William R. Rowland]]. Rowland sent a posse to the ranch and captured Vasquez on May 14, 1874. Greek George's adobe was situated near the present-day Melrose Place in West Hollywood, very close to where the movie industry set up shop a few decades later.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_309\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=309\u2013319}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/sfc051574a.htm | title=Vasquez Captured At Last. | publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Historical Society | accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\nVasquez remained in the [[Los Angeles County]] jail for nine days. He had numerous requests for interviews by many newspaper reporters, but agreed to see only three: two from the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' and one from the ''Los Angeles Star''. He told them his aim was to return California to Mexican rule. He insisted he was an honorable man and claimed he had never killed anyone. He was photographed by [[Valentin Wolfenstein]] behind the jail on May 18, 1874.<ref name=cslfdn>{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2012|p=6}}</ref>\n\nIn late May, Vasquez was moved by steamship to [[San Francisco]]. He eventually stood trial in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]. Vasquez quickly became a celebrity among many of his fellow [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] Californians. He admitted he was an outlaw, but again denied he had ever killed anyone. A note purportedly written by Clodoveo Ch\u00e1vez, one of his gang members, was dropped into a Wells Fargo box. Ch\u00e1vez wrote that he, not Vasquez, had shot the men at Tres Pinos. Nevertheless, at his trial Vasquez admitted participating in the Tres Pinos raid. Since all the participants in the robbery were equally guilty of any murder that took place during its commission, whether Vasquez actually pulled the trigger was legally irrelevant. In January 1875, Vasquez was convicted and sentenced to hang for murder. His trial had taken four days and the jury deliberated for only two hours before finally finding him guilty of one count of murder in the Tres Pinos robbery.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_327\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=327\u2013348}}</ref>\n\nVisitors still flocked to Vasquez's jail cell, many of them women. He signed autographs and posed for photographs. Vasquez sold the photos from the window of his cell and used the money to pay for his legal defense. After his conviction, he appealed for clemency. It was denied by Governor [[Romualdo Pacheco]]. Vasquez calmly met his fate in San Jose on March 19, 1875. He was 39 years old.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_349\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=349\u2013366}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nEven today, Tiburcio V\u00e1squez remains controversial. He is seen as a hero by some for his defiance of what he viewed as unjust laws and discrimination. Others regard him as a colorful outlaw. To this day, many continue to visit and pay respects to Vasquez's grave. He was buried in [[Mission Santa Clara de As\u00eds|Santa Clara Mission Cemetery]] in Santa Clara, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legendsofamerica.com/we-tiburciovasquez/|title=Tiburcio Vasquez \u2013 California Desperado|last=|first=|date=|website=Legends of America|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nHis grave is very difficult to find, but visitors to Santa Clara cemetery have managed to find it for years. The groundskeeper directed Vasquez relative, Patrick McAnaney, to the grave in 1980, telling him \"Vasquez lived at odds with the people, and he was buried at odds with them.\" This was in reference to his gravestone being set at an angle relative to the other gravestones. \n\nAs of Aug 12, 2017, historian and Psychic Medium, Michael J. Kouri and friends found his grave after a long search. Online photos show his grave beside two large cacti and in front of a palm tree, no longer standing. However, they fail to mention that his carved granite headstone is the only stone in the entire cemetery to stand at an angle. All the rest are in uniform rows, and many other graves surrounding Vasquez's grave are flat to the ground as if no one else wanted to be interred near the famous bandido until decades later when his fame had died down. Vasquez's ghost is said to haunt many places, including the cemetery, some of his hideouts, areas where gruesome crimes were committed, and the prison cells where he was held.\n\nWith his upper-class [[Californio]] background, Vasquez is thought to have been one of several sources for the bandit-hero character [[Zorro]].<ref>{{harvnb|Deutch|2008|}}</ref>\n\nThe actor [[Anthony Caruso (actor)|Anthony Caruso]] played Vasquez in ''[[Stories of the Century]].''\n\nArmand Alzamora (1928\u20132009) played Vasquez in the 1957 episode, \"The Last Bad Man\" of the syndicated anthology series, ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', hosted by [[Stanley Andrews]]. The segment focuses on Vasquez's early life of crime, his hatred for the [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo|US takeover of California]], the prison escape, and his hanging at the age of 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556823/|title=The Last Bad Man on ''Death Valley Days''|publisher=Internet Movie Data Base|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe trunk and knife that belonged to Tiburcio are on display at the [[Andres Pico Adobe]] in [[Mission Hills, Los Angeles|Mission Hills]], part of the [[San Fernando Valley Historical Society]] collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiahistoricalsociety.blogspot.com/2016/08/history-keepers-knife-and-trunk-of.html|title=History Keepers: Knife and Trunk of Tiburcio Vasquez|last=|first=|date=2016-08-03|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Places named for Vasquez ===\n==== Geographical features ====\n* [[Vasquez Rocks]], an area of distinctive rock formations in the [[Sierra Pelona Mountains]] that is popular as a filming location for movies and television\n* Vasquez Canyon in [[Saugus, California]]\n* Vasquez Tree, outside of the 21-mile house, in [[Morgan Hill, California]]\n* Vasquez day use area in the [[Angeles National Forest]]\n* Tiburcio's X and (Vasquez's) Monolith, two rock faces popular with climbers in [[Pinnacles National Park, California|Pinnacles National Park]], were named for the legend that Vasquez hid out in a cave below the Monolith.<ref>{{harvnb|Rubine|1995|pp=12,55,62}}</ref>\n\n==== Buildings and facilities ====\n* Tiburcio Vasquez Health Center, [[Hayward, California]] and [[Union City, California|Union City]]<ref>{{harvnb|Our History: What's in a name?|2013}}</ref>\n* Vasquez High School in [[Acton, California#Education|Acton, California]]\n* The Alisal Union School District near [[Salinas, California]] named a new school Tiburcio Vasquez Elementary School in 2012. The choice of name attracted much criticism and the school was renamed to Monte Bella Elementary in 2016.<ref name=\"SaidCNN\">{{harvnb|Said|2013|}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|title=Bandido: The Life and Times of Tiburcio Vasquez|date=2010|first=John|last=Boessenecker}}\n* [[Eugene T. Sawyer|Sawyer, Eugene T.]] and William H Collins. [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.32106016176981&view=1up&seq=17 ''The Life And Career of Tiburcio Vasquez: the California Stage Robber'']. Oakland, Calif.: Biobooks, 1944\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.tvhc.org/AboutUs/History.aspx |title=Our History: What's in a name? |publisher=Tiburcio Vasquez Health Center |accessdate=July 7, 2014 |ref={{harvid|Our History: What's in a name?|2013}}}}\n* {{Citation |last= Acu\u00f1a |first= Rodolfo F. |authorlink= Rodolfo F. Acu\u00f1a |title= Occupied America: A History of Chicanos |edition= 7th |year= 2011 |publisher= Longman |location= Boston |isbn= 978-0-205-78618-3}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.cslfdn.org/pdf/Bulletin102.pdf |title= Bandido: The Countless Love Affairs of Tiburcio Vasquez |first=John |last=Boessenecker |date=2012 |website= Bulletin |publisher=California State Library Foundation |pages=6\u201311 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}\n* {{Citation |last=Boessenecker |first=John |title=Bandido: The Life and Times of Tiburcio Vasquez |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-8061-4127-5 |location=Norman, Oklahoma}}\n* McLean, Angus, Legends of the California Bandidos, Arroyo Grande, CA 1989.\n* May, Ernest, \"Tiburcio Vasquez,\" Furia y Muerte: Los Bandidos Chicanos, eds. Castillo, Pedro & Albert Camarillo.\n* {{cite book |last=Roddy |first=W. Lee |date=1970 |title=Wanted! Black Bart and Other California Outlaws |url= |location=Ceres, California }}\n* {{citation |title=Climber's Guide to Pinnacles National Monument |first=David |last=Rubine |publisher=[[Globe Pequot]] |year=1995 |isbn=9780934641890 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NcBQRmAXCP4C&pg=PA12 }}\n* {{cite web |last=Said |first=Samira |title=Villain or hero? Flap over California school named for bandit |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/03/us/california-school-name-controversy/index.html?hpt=hp_t3 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=January 3, 2013 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Thrapp |first=Dan L. |contribution=Vasquez, Tiburcio |title=Encyclopedia of Frontier Biography |publisher=The Arthur H. Clark Co. |place=Spokane, WA |year=1990}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.canyon-news.com/artman2/publish/DegreesCoolerfeb/In_the_Hills_Truth_Meets_Fiction_printer.php |first=Joann |last=Deutch |date=August 10, 2008 |website=Canyon News |title=In The Hills Truth Meets Fiction |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509105317/http://www.canyon-news.com/artman2/publish/DegreesCoolerfeb/In_the_Hills_Truth_Meets_Fiction_printer.php |archivedate=May 9, 2016 |df= }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.legendsofamerica.com/we-tiburciovasquez.html Vasquez on Legends of America]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060907222205/http://www.picacho.org/interest/tiburcio-vasquez.html Tiburcio Vasquez]\n* [http://www.californiahistory.com/sample.html Tiburcio Vasquez in Southern California: The Bandit's Last Hurrah]\n\n{{Wild West}}\n\n{{American tall tales}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vasquez, Tiburcio}}\n[[Category:1835 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1854]]\n[[Category:Californios]]\n[[Category:People of Mexican California]]\n[[Category:Mexican folklore]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Mexican outlaws]]\n[[Category:People executed by California by hanging]]\n[[Category:Mexican people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from California]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions by the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:Mexican people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mission Santa Clara de As\u00eds]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:People of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Executed Mexican people]]\n[[Category:People from Monterey, California]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from California]]\n[[Category:1850s murders in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Californian bandit}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Tiburcio Vasquez\n| image_name = Tiburcio Vasquez.png\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1835|04|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Monterey]], [[Alta California]], [[First Mexican Republic]]<br/>{{small|(today [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]])}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1875|03|19|1835|08|11}}\n| death_place = [[San Jose, California|San Jos\u00e9]], California \n| death_cause = [[Execution by hanging]]\n| conviction = Murder\n| conviction_penalty = Death by hanging\n| conviction_status = Executed\n}}\n\n'''Tiburcio Vasquez''' (April 11, 1835 \u2013 March 19, 1875) was a [[Californio]] [[Outlaw|''bandido'']] who was active in [[California]] from 1854 to 1874. The [[Vasquez Rocks]], {{convert|40|mi}} north of [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], were one of his many hideouts and are named after him.\n\n== Early life ==\nTiburcio Vasquez was born in [[Monterey]], [[Alta California]], Mexico (present-day [[California]], United States) on April 11, 1835 to Jos\u00e9 Hermenegildo Vasquez and Mar\u00eda Guadalupe Cantua.<ref name=\"Acu\u00f1a\">{{harvnb|Acu\u00f1a|2011|p=140}}</ref><ref name=\"Boessenecker_013\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|p=13}}</ref> In accord with Spanish tradition, Vasquez's birth was celebrated on the feast day of his namesake, St. Tiburtius. Thus, he always referred to his birthday as August 11, 1835.<ref name=\"Boessenecker\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010}}</ref> His great-grandfather came to Alta California with the [[De Anza Expedition]] of 1776. Vasquez was slightly built,  about {{convert|5|ft|7|in|cm}}. His family sent him to school, and he was fluent in both English and Spanish.\n\nIn 1852, Vasquez was influenced by [[Anastacio Garc\u00eda]], one of California's most dangerous bandits.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_046\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=46\u201348}}</ref> In 1854, Vasquez was present at the slaying of Monterey Constable William Hardmount in a fight with Anastacio Garc\u00eda at a [[fandango (dance)|fandango]]. Vasquez denied any involvement and fled, becoming an outlaw. Vasquez later claimed his crimes were the result of discrimination by the ''norteamericanos'' and insisted that he was a defender of Mexican-American rights.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_049\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=49\u201353}}</ref> Vasquez and Garc\u00eda played leading roles in Monterey County's murderous Roach-Belcher feud, which ended when Garc\u00eda was executed by hanging in 1875.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_054-069\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=54\u201369}}</ref>\n\nBy 1856, Vasquez was rustling horses. A sheriff's posse caught up with him near [[Santa Clarita, California|Newhall]], and he spent the next five years behind bars in [[San Quentin]] prison. There he helped organize, and participated in, four bloody prison breaks which left twenty convicts dead.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_070\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=70\u2013101}}</ref> After his release, he committed numerous burglaries, cattle thefts, and highway robberies in Sonoma County in 1866. He was captured after a store burglary in [[Petaluma]] and sent to prison again for three years.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_102\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=102\u2013120}}</ref> His \"trademark\" was \"binding [his victims'] hands behind their back and leaving them face down in the dust.\"<ref name=\"Roddy\">{{harvnb|Roddy|1970}}</ref>\n\n== Final years ==\nIn 1870, Vasquez organized a bandit gang, which included the notorious Juan Soto, and later, [[Procopio|Procopio Bustamante]]. After numerous bandit raids, he was shot and badly wounded in a gunfight with [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]] police officer Robert Liddell. He managed to escape, and his sisters nursed him back to health.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_165\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=165\u2013172}}</ref>\n\nIn 1873, he gained statewide, and then nationwide, notoriety. Vasquez and his gang stole $2,200 from Snyder's Store in [[Tres Pinos]], now called [[Paicines, California|Paicines]], in [[San Benito County]], three were killed, but not by Tiburcio. [[Posse Comitatus (Common Law)|Posses]] began searching for him, and Governor [[Newton Booth]] placed a $1,000 reward on his head. Sheriff John H. Adams from San Jose pursued the band to Southern California; Vasquez escaped after a gunfight.<ref>{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=213\u2013241}}</ref>\n\nVasquez hid for a while in Southern California, where he was less well known. With his two most trusted men, he rode over the [[Tejon Pass (Kern County)|old Tejon Pass]], through the [[Antelope Valley]], and rested at Jim Hefner's ranch at [[Elizabeth Lake (Los Angeles County, California)|Elizabeth Lake]]. Vasquez's brother, Francisco, lived nearby. After resting, Vasquez rode on to [[Littlerock, California|Littlerock]] Creek, which became his first [[Southern California]] hideout.\n\nVasquez was popular in the Mexican-American community, and had many friends and family members from Santa Rosa in Northern California to Los Angeles in the south. He was handsome, literate, charming, played guitar, and was a skillful dancer. Women were attracted to him and he had many love affairs. He enjoyed reading romantic novels and writing poetry for his female admirers. He had several affairs with married women, one of which eventually led to his downfall.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_139\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=139\u2013140, 206\u2013207, 233\u2013234}}</ref>\n\nVasquez returned to the San Joaquin Valley. On November 10, 1873, he and his gang robbed the Jones store at Millerton in Fresno County. On December 26, 1873, he and his band sacked the town of [[Kingston, California|Kingston]] in [[Fresno County]], robbing all the businesses and making off with $2,500 in cash and jewelry.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_250\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=250\u2013268}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Booth was now authorized by the California State Legislature to spend up to $15,000 to bring the law down on Vasquez. Posses were formed in [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]], [[Monterey County, California|Monterey]], [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]], Fresno, and [[Tulare County, California|Tulare]] counties. In January 1874, Booth offered $3,000 for Vasquez's capture alive, and $2,000 if he was brought back dead. These rewards were increased in February to $8,000 and $6,000, respectively. [[Alameda County, California|Alameda County]] Sheriff Harry Morse was assigned specifically to track down Vasquez.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_271\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=271\u2013285}}</ref>\n\nHeading towards [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], Vasquez and gang member, Clodoveo Ch\u00e1vez, rode to the rock promontory near [[Inyokern, California|Inyokern]] now known as [[Robbers Roost (Kern County, California)|Robbers Roost]]. Near that spot, at Coyote Holes, they robbed a stagecoach from the [[Cerro Gordo Mines]], silver mines near [[Owens Lake]]. During the robbery Vasquez shot and wounded a man who did not obey his orders.\n\nThe gang moved to Elizabeth Lake and [[Soledad Canyon]], robbing a stage of $300, stealing six horses and a wagon near present-day [[Acton, California|Acton]], and robbing lone travelers. Vasquez was believed to be hiding out at Vasquez Rocks.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_289\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=289\u2013290}}</ref> These rock formations proved a formidable hideout for him and his gang. Shallow caves, deep crevices, and numerous overhangs created a maze for any posse to thread. The tallest rock, 150 feet (46&nbsp;m) high, provided an excellent lookout point.\n\nFor the next two months, he escaped attention. However, he then made an error that led to his capture. On April 15, 1874, he and his band held the prominent sheepman, Alessandro Repetto, for ransom. Pursuing posses from Los Angeles almost trapped the gang in the San Gabriel Mountains, but once again, Vasquez and his men escaped.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_293\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=293\u2013302}}</ref>\n\n== Capture ==\n[[File:Map of Tiburcio V\u00e1squez Capture.jpg|thumb|Vintage Map of Tiburcio V\u00e1squez Capture]]\nVasquez took up residence at the adobe home of [[Yiorgos Caralambo|\"Greek George\" Caralambo]] in the northwest corner of [[Rancho La Brea]], located 200 yards (183&nbsp;m) south of the present-day [[Sunset Strip]] in [[West Hollywood]]. Greek George was a former [[camel]] driver for General [[Edward Fitzgerald Beale|Beale]] in the [[United States Army|Army]] [[U.S. Camel Corps|Camel Corps]]. Allegedly, Vasquez seduced and impregnated his own niece. Either the girl's family or Greek George's wife's family betrayed Vasquez to Los Angeles Sheriff [[William R. Rowland]]. Rowland sent a posse to the ranch and captured Vasquez on May 14, 1874. Greek George's adobe was situated near the present-day Melrose Place in West Hollywood, very close to where the movie industry set up shop a few decades later.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_309\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=309\u2013319}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scvhistory.com/scvhistory/sfc051574a.htm | title=Vasquez Captured At Last. | publisher=Santa Clarita Valley Historical Society | accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\nVasquez remained in the [[Los Angeles County]] jail for nine days. He had numerous requests for interviews by many newspaper reporters, but agreed to see only three: two from the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' and one from the ''Los Angeles Star''. He told them his aim was to return California to Mexican rule. He insisted he was an honorable man and claimed he had never killed anyone. He was photographed by [[Valentin Wolfenstein]] behind the jail on May 18, 1874.<ref name=cslfdn>{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2012|p=6}}</ref>\n\nIn late May, Vasquez was moved by steamship to [[San Francisco]]. He eventually stood trial in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]. Vasquez quickly became a celebrity among many of his fellow [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] Californians. He admitted he was an outlaw, but again denied he had ever killed anyone. A note purportedly written by Clodoveo Ch\u00e1vez, one of his gang members, was dropped into a Wells Fargo box. Ch\u00e1vez wrote that he, not Vasquez, had shot the men at Tres Pinos. Nevertheless, at his trial Vasquez admitted participating in the Tres Pinos raid. Since all the participants in the robbery were equally guilty of any murder that took place during its commission, whether Vasquez actually pulled the trigger was legally irrelevant. In January 1875, Vasquez was convicted and sentenced to hang for murder. His trial had taken four days and the jury deliberated for only two hours before finally finding him guilty of one count of murder in the Tres Pinos robbery.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_327\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=327\u2013348}}</ref>\n\nVisitors still flocked to Vasquez's jail cell, many of them women. He signed autographs and posed for photographs. Vasquez sold the photos from the window of his cell and used the money to pay for his legal defense. After his conviction, he appealed for clemency. It was denied by Governor [[Romualdo Pacheco]]. Vasquez calmly met his fate in San Jose on March 19, 1875. He was 39 years old.<ref name=\"Boessenecker_349\">{{harvnb|Boessenecker|2010|pp=349\u2013366}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nEven today, Tiburcio V\u00e1squez remains controversial. He is seen as a hero by some for his defiance of what he viewed as unjust laws and discrimination. Others regard him as a colorful outlaw. To this day, many continue to visit and pay respects to Vasquez's grave. He was buried in [[Mission Santa Clara de As\u00eds|Santa Clara Mission Cemetery]] in Santa Clara, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legendsofamerica.com/we-tiburciovasquez/|title=Tiburcio Vasquez \u2013 California Desperado|last=|first=|date=|website=Legends of America|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nHis grave is very difficult to find, but visitors to Santa Clara cemetery have managed to find it for years. The groundskeeper directed Vasquez relative, Patrick McAnaney, to the grave in 1980, telling him \"Vasquez lived at odds with the people, and he was buried at odds with them.\" This was in reference to his gravestone being set at an angle relative to the other gravestones. \n\nAs of Aug 12, 2017, historian and Psychic Medium, Michael J. Kouri and friends found his grave after a long search. Online photos show his grave beside two large cacti and in front of a palm tree, no longer standing. However, they fail to mention that his carved granite headstone is the only stone in the entire cemetery to stand at an angle. All the rest are in uniform rows, and many other graves surrounding Vasquez's grave are flat to the ground as if no one else wanted to be interred near the famous bandido until decades later when his fame had died down. Vasquez's ghost is said to haunt many places, including the cemetery, some of his hideouts, areas where gruesome crimes were committed, and the prison cells where he was held.\n\nWith his upper-class [[Californio]] background, Vasquez is thought to have been one of several sources for the bandit-hero character [[Zorro]].<ref>{{harvnb|Deutch|2008|}}</ref>\n\nThe actor [[Anthony Caruso (actor)|Anthony Caruso]] played Vasquez in ''[[Stories of the Century]].''\n\nArmand Alzamora (1928\u20132009) played Vasquez in the 1957 episode, \"The Last Bad Man\" of the syndicated anthology series, ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', hosted by [[Stanley Andrews]]. The segment focuses on Vasquez's early life of crime, his hatred for the [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo|US takeover of California]], the prison escape, and his hanging at the age of 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556823/|title=The Last Bad Man on ''Death Valley Days''|publisher=Internet Movie Data Base|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe trunk and knife that belonged to Tiburcio are on display at the [[Andres Pico Adobe]] in [[Mission Hills, Los Angeles|Mission Hills]], part of the [[San Fernando Valley Historical Society]] collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiahistoricalsociety.blogspot.com/2016/08/history-keepers-knife-and-trunk-of.html|title=History Keepers: Knife and Trunk of Tiburcio Vasquez|last=|first=|date=2016-08-03|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Places named for Vasquez ===\n==== Geographical features ====\n* [[Vasquez Rocks]], an area of distinctive rock formations in the [[Sierra Pelona Mountains]] that is popular as a filming location for movies and television\n* Vasquez Canyon in [[Saugus, California]]\n* Vasquez Tree, outside of the 21-mile house, in [[Morgan Hill, California]]\n* Vasquez day use area in the [[Angeles National Forest]]\n* Tiburcio's X and (Vasquez's) Monolith, two rock faces popular with climbers in [[Pinnacles National Park, California|Pinnacles National Park]], were named for the legend that Vasquez hid out in a cave below the Monolith.<ref>{{harvnb|Rubine|1995|pp=12,55,62}}</ref>\n\n==== Buildings and facilities ====\n* Tiburcio Vasquez Health Center, [[Hayward, California]] and [[Union City, California|Union City]]<ref>{{harvnb|Our History: What's in a name?|2013}}</ref>\n* Vasquez High School in [[Acton, California#Education|Acton, California]]\n* The Alisal Union School District near [[Salinas, California]] named a new school Tiburcio Vasquez Elementary School in 2012. The choice of name attracted much criticism and the school was renamed to Monte Bella Elementary in 2016.<ref name=\"SaidCNN\">{{harvnb|Said|2013|}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|title=Bandido: The Life and Times of Tiburcio Vasquez|date=2010|first=John|last=Boessenecker}}\n* [[Eugene T. Sawyer|Sawyer, Eugene T.]] and William H Collins. [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.32106016176981&view=1up&seq=17 ''The Life And Career of Tiburcio Vasquez: the California Stage Robber'']. Oakland, Calif.: Biobooks, 1944\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.tvhc.org/AboutUs/History.aspx |title=Our History: What's in a name? |publisher=Tiburcio Vasquez Health Center |accessdate=July 7, 2014 |ref={{harvid|Our History: What's in a name?|2013}}}}\n* {{Citation |last= Acu\u00f1a |first= Rodolfo F. |authorlink= Rodolfo F. Acu\u00f1a |title= Occupied America: A History of Chicanos |edition= 7th |year= 2011 |publisher= Longman |location= Boston |isbn= 978-0-205-78618-3}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.cslfdn.org/pdf/Bulletin102.pdf |title= Bandido: The Countless Love Affairs of Tiburcio Vasquez |first=John |last=Boessenecker |date=2012 |website= Bulletin |publisher=California State Library Foundation |pages=6\u201311 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}\n* {{Citation |last=Boessenecker |first=John |title=Bandido: The Life and Times of Tiburcio Vasquez |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-8061-4127-5 |location=Norman, Oklahoma}}\n* McLean, Angus, Legends of the California Bandidos, Arroyo Grande, CA 1989.\n* May, Ernest, \"Tiburcio Vasquez,\" Furia y Muerte: Los Bandidos Chicanos, eds. Castillo, Pedro & Albert Camarillo.\n* {{cite book |last=Roddy |first=W. Lee |date=1970 |title=Wanted! Black Bart and Other California Outlaws |url= |location=Ceres, California }}\n* {{citation |title=Climber's Guide to Pinnacles National Monument |first=David |last=Rubine |publisher=[[Globe Pequot]] |year=1995 |isbn=9780934641890 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NcBQRmAXCP4C&pg=PA12 }}\n* {{cite web |last=Said |first=Samira |title=Villain or hero? Flap over California school named for bandit |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/03/us/california-school-name-controversy/index.html?hpt=hp_t3 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=January 3, 2013 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Thrapp |first=Dan L. |contribution=Vasquez, Tiburcio |title=Encyclopedia of Frontier Biography |publisher=The Arthur H. Clark Co. |place=Spokane, WA |year=1990}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.canyon-news.com/artman2/publish/DegreesCoolerfeb/In_the_Hills_Truth_Meets_Fiction_printer.php |first=Joann |last=Deutch |date=August 10, 2008 |website=Canyon News |title=In The Hills Truth Meets Fiction |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509105317/http://www.canyon-news.com/artman2/publish/DegreesCoolerfeb/In_the_Hills_Truth_Meets_Fiction_printer.php |archivedate=May 9, 2016 |df= }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.legendsofamerica.com/we-tiburciovasquez.html Vasquez on Legends of America]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060907222205/http://www.picacho.org/interest/tiburcio-vasquez.html Tiburcio Vasquez]\n* [http://www.californiahistory.com/sample.html Tiburcio Vasquez in Southern California: The Bandit's Last Hurrah]\n\n{{Wild West}}\n\n{{American tall tales}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vasquez, Tiburcio}}\n[[Category:1835 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1854]]\n[[Category:Californios]]\n[[Category:People of Mexican California]]\n[[Category:Mexican folklore]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Mexican outlaws]]\n[[Category:People executed by California by hanging]]\n[[Category:Mexican people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from California]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions by the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:Mexican people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mission Santa Clara de As\u00eds]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:People of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Executed Mexican people]]\n[[Category:People from Monterey, California]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from California]]\n[[Category:1850s murders in the United States]]\